r high growth operators. More than 30 Not Boring readers have already hired=
 an EA+ through Oceans. If you=E2=80=99re looking to level-up your producti=
vity, check them out today.
(1) The First Room-Temperature Ambient-Pressure Superconductor [ https://li=
nk.sbstck.com/redirect/9ba2c7b2-1278-4661-9bc1-d9f16421d305?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
We believe that our new development will be a brand-new historical event th=
at opens a new era for humankind.
Packy here. On Tuesday, a group of South Korean scientists dropped a paper =
on arXiv claiming that they=E2=80=99d created the world=E2=80=99s first roo=
m-temperature ambient-pressure superconductor.=20
If you=E2=80=99re new to the Superconductor Fan Club, like me and thousands=
 of others, this June thread from fusion engineer Andrew Cote [ https://lin=
k.sbstck.com/redirect/713994fc-bf57-4c1a-8d20-ad32cb00a1d3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] gives a great overview=
, and some reasons to get excited:=20
Room-temperature superconductivity is the holy-grail in fundamental materia=
l science and would create a dramatic technological transformation. High-sp=
eed mag-lev trains, desktop quantum computers, compact affordable fusion re=
actors, lossless long-range power transmission.
On Tuesday morning, I didn=E2=80=99t really know what room-temperature supe=
rconductivity was. Three days later, I deeply understand that it is the mos=
t important material in the world and the fate of humanity rests on whether=
 or not the paper=E2=80=99s results replicate.  =20
I first heard about it from Ryan McEntush=E2=80=99s tweet:=20
Since that tweet, we=E2=80=99ve whiplashed between =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re s=
o back=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s so over=E2=80=9D at internet spee=
d. From =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s just simple diamagnetism=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=
=9Cthe paper=E2=80=99s authors have to believe this is real because three o=
f them broke from the six-person group to rush print a paper with only thre=
e authors because the Nobel can only be shared by three people=E2=80=9D to =
=E2=80=9Cwait we=E2=80=99re back again there=E2=80=99s a peer reviewed pape=
r from April in Korean [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/b0e3afde-d3a6-466=
8-aa3e-d5c99dbfd550?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ] that has better graphs=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s prob=
ably just a cool magnet.=E2=80=9D The latest is that a team from MIT has fl=
own to South Korea [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/7757cb08-a4a6-46e0-9e=
14-5bee116ed6c1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] to work with the papers=E2=80=99 authors on replicating.=20
No idea how this is going to turn out. It=E2=80=99s been fun following Ate-=
a-Pi [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/5233534d-c805-4da6-a8d9-f89330f6cba=
8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and =
Alex Kaplan [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/47a77163-9cba-4ffa-8a6c-d761=
dd4bbc61?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] for the latest developments. The reason I wanted to lead off with this s=
tory isn=E2=80=99t that I=E2=80=99m sure this is a RTSC and the world is go=
ing to change forever, but because it=E2=80=99s been so cool getting to wat=
ch this all play out live on Twitter (X?).=20
There=E2=80=99s been a pragmatic optimism around the whole thing that I don=
=E2=80=99t think would have been there a year ago. Non-scientists are getti=
ng hyped about materials science and physics. Materials scientists and phys=
icists are sharing what they know with a balance of optimism and skepticism=
=2E Everyone is rooting for replicat=
ion. We=E2=80=99re getting to see the sci=
entific process play out in real-time. And some people are even trying to r=
eplicate themselves.=20
Varda [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/63b70cfe-63d1-41c2-9cf2-353509c4e8=
57?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] eng=
ineer Andrew McCalip [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/a63b9c02-a62a-41b9-=
9b7b-cb0a7186bf8d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ] is leading a group of engineers in trying to replicate the resu=
lts at Varda=E2=80=99s facility after-hours: Meissner Effect or Bust. They=
=E2=80=99re livestreaming on Twitch [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/a199=
a303-7aa4-4764-ba9d-fced6e0cb2f4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (2,014 people watching now, down from 16k before=
 their wifi went down).=20
I hope they=E2=80=99re able to replicate. Room-temperature superconductors =
could unlock a lot of sci-fi tech and improve a lot of peoples=E2=80=99 liv=
es. But either way, this kind of enthusiasm is great to see. It=E2=80=99s l=
ike the I-95 rebuild [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/e75efcd7-f553-4d79-=
9933-3bf2a645a8d8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ] for science. We=E2=80=99re getting excited about the right kind=
 of things again. Superconductor or not, we are so back.=20
(2) The Startup Trying to Prevent World War 3 [ https://link.sbstck.com/red=
irect/0b724e04-a1de-44b8-b587-9ebb8b28485f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Anduril is building the Lockheed Martin of the 21st Century. Its mission is=
 to transform the U.S. military and national security capabilities with adv=
anced technology.=20
Not Boring Investment Memo, 2022 (disclosure: we=E2=80=99re investors)
Speaking of getting excited about all the right things again=E2=80=A6 Found=
ers Fund EIR John Coogan [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/0a7eac77-4483-4=
10c-936b-f6ab55fe7195?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ] tells the Anduril [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/b29786=
c8-d262-48cb-9dbb-dd979d2e2918?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] story masterfully in this 42 minute Youtube video,=
 with exclusive access to company execs, government insiders, and investors=
=2E=20
Founded over six years ago, the company faced harsh media scrutiny for work=
ing with the DoD at a time when many tech companies (particularly their emp=
loyees) thought that was a morally wrong thing to do. Then Russia invaded U=
kraine, and ensuring that America had access to the best technology the wor=
ld had to offer became an Obviously Good Thing.=20
Anduril used that uncertainty window [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/02e=
554c4-1253-47c5-919b-7069075ecca0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to build out an AI-powered operating system, La=
ttice, and a range of hardware products built for modern warfare. Those pro=
ducts are proving to be the right tools for the kind of war being fought in=
 Ukraine.=20
It=E2=80=99s also hired a team of mission-minded technologists who want to =
work on a Good Quest [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/c52fd29a-f3a1-42c4-=
9957-8c9538775239?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ] but would never work somewhere like Lockheed Martin or Northrop=
 Grumman. If you=E2=80=99re a young ambitious technologist, would you rathe=
r work at Google getting people to click links or Anduril building the tech=
nologies that could protect your country from harm? U.S.A. U.S.A. U.S.A.=20
Now that what Anduril is doing is obvious, it=E2=80=99s well on its way to =
becoming the sixth Defense Prime by offering capabilities that the other fi=
ve can=E2=80=99t.=20
John tells the story better than we will, so put down the PinkyDoll and wat=
ch the doc this weekend.=20
(3) The US government is taking a serious step toward space-based nuclear p=
ropulsion [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/87c87461-796a-400f-a180-9ecbfd=
ba720a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
NASA announced Wednesday that it is partnering with the US Department of De=
fense to launch a nuclear-powered rocket engine into space as early as 2027=
=2E The US space agency will invest abo=
ut $300 million in the project to deve=
lop a next-generation propulsion system for in-space transportation.
Speaking of prime contractors, NASA announced that it will be launching a n=
uclear-powered rocket engine into space in the next couple of years, in par=
tnership with DARPA, Lockheed Martin, SpaceX, and a number of other governm=
ental agencies.
Traditional chemical propulsion is great for getting rockets off the ground=
, but is not terribly efficient for solar system exploration because fuel i=
s heavy. Nuclear propulsion, on the other hand, has the potential to be far=
 more efficient and would enable longer and farther expeditions=E2=80=A6 li=
ke Mars.=20
This nuclear propulsion system is what NASA is betting us will get us to Ma=
rs. Of course, a lot has to go right both with this initial and subsequent =
tests. Namely, you know, nuclear reactions in space. But these are the type=
s of big swings we love seeing NASA and its partners take. Plus, it might p=
rovide another push to turn public opinion on nuclear towards reality befor=
e it=E2=80=99s too late.=20
(4) Rewiring cancer drivers to activate apoptosis [ https://link.sbstck.com=
/redirect/73019247-d2e3-40ec-992a-89753f262d75?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
The coexistence of cell death pathways with driver mutations suggests that =
the cancer driver could be rewired to activate cell death using chemical in=
ducers of proximity (CIPs). Here we describe a new class of molecules calle=
d transcriptional/epigenetic CIPs (TCIPs) that recruit the endogenous cance=
r driver, or a downstream transcription factor, to the promoters of cell de=
ath genes, thereby activating their expression.
A team of Stanford researchers have developed a concept for making cancer c=
ells self-destruct. In a new paper published this week in Nature [ https://=
link.sbstck.com/redirect/73019247-d2e3-40ec-992a-89753f262d75?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the team explained=
 how we could hook cancer driving molecules to other molecules in a way tha=
t would cause self-destruction. Essentially, we could turn the molecules th=
at drive cancer growth into cancer killers.=20
I am few IQ points and a couple of decades of education away from truly und=
erstanding how all of this works. And according to the researchers, we=E2=
=80=99re still a bit of a ways off from transforming this concept into a dr=
ug that could save lives. But the molecular concept (pictured above) is nov=
el in that it has never appeared before in nature and could potentially wor=
k on half of all cancers.
(5) LLaMA2 Chat 70B vs. ChatGPT [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/68aa8db8=
-fbce-4649-af78-3742735857e1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Last week we covered how Meta was open sourcing its large language model, L=
lama2 =E2=80=94 essentially giving away for free what OpenAI has built its =
business and reputation around. Now, a Llama-based chat bot (which you can =
check out on Hugging Face here [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/a9d944d6-=
0a86-46c8-aa20-e9670efde059?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]) is reportedly outperforming the standard ChatGPT. Op=
enAI=E2=80=99s more advanced GPT-4 model still outperforms the LlaMA2 Chat =
70B. For how long, though? Only time will tell.
Tracking the ins-and-outs of LLM performance is not exactly our beat here a=
t Not Boring. There are hundreds (now thousands?) of AI-specific newsletter=
s that have popped up to do that in recent months. But, it is wild to see t=
he rise of competition and the speed of progress in such a nascent space. C=
hatGPT shocked the world just 8 months ago, and now there are a plethora of=
 well-resourced and performant alternatives.=20
Open-source foundation models competing with closed ones should be a boon f=
or innovation in the space and a counterbalance against centralized control=
 of the digital brains.=20
Bonus: An Investor's Introduction to Urbit - Part 1 [ https://link.sbstck.c=
om/redirect/2549496d-b6e9-4485-ac82-565bd93decc9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
By Basho
Urbit is a personal computer that runs in the cloud and natively combines a=
 unique identity (in the form of an NFT), data storage (via an integrated d=
atabase), application execution (which is run server-side, i.e. by the indi=
vidual user) and P2P networking. The result is a system in which users cont=
rol all of their own data and applications, and can easily interact with al=
l other users on the network without reliance on centralized companies.
Packy here again. Last year, we invested in Tlon [ https://link.sbstck.com/=
redirect/ca6b90d1-acff-44c9-9417-24938415b0d7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the core developer of Urbit, the=
=E2=80=A6 it=E2=80=99s complicated.=20
Urbit is one of the most ambitious software projects ever created. It=E2=80=
=99s a personal computer in the cloud and a personal state machine. It has =
its own language, Hoon, and offers a dramatically simpler way to develop so=
ftware by removing the need for DevOps. It has social features built in, bu=
t it=E2=80=99s not a social network.=20
Basho, the pseudonymous author of this piece, wrote the best Urbit explaine=
r I=E2=80=99ve come across yet. In one sentence, he writes, =E2=80=9CUrbit =
is what the personal computer would look like if it had been built from fir=
st principles today.=E2=80=9D Then he dives deeper to explain Urbit for bot=
h crypto-natives and everyone else.=20
What I like most about the piece is that Basho gets as specific as possible=
 about Urbit=E2=80=99s benefits. =E2=80=9CData sovereignty=E2=80=9D is cool=
, for example, but most people don=E2=80=99t care about data sovereignty on=
 its own. They care about it only as far as it can provide a better experie=
nce: =E2=80=9CThe insight here is that data sovereignty, while valuable in =
its own right, is actually a prerequisite for this improved computing exper=
ience.=E2=80=9D
The Urbit rabbit hole is deep. Basho=E2=80=99s piece (with more to come) is=
 a good place to dive in.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

